## Part 4 – Institutional Applications

This application uses the capability lens to examine how different institutional doctrines perform over time under a common trust environment. 

The objective is not to optimise a particular insurance product, but to test how combinations of underwriting discipline, capital management, and renewal behaviour behave as institutional capabilities within the Trust Framework.

# Application A: Capability Lens – Marine Insurance Trust Market (SIM F)

This section will present a detailed case study of the Trust Framework
applied to a multi-agent marine insurance market. The SIM F model
implements contribution, trust, credibility, credit, coordination,
coexistent systems, and continuation in a single simulation engine.

## Role of SIM F in the Trust Framework
SIM F is a self‑contained simulation of a marine insurance market with multiple agents writing shared risks. 

It is not part of the core Trust Framework; rather, it serves as a worked example showing how the abstract layers of:

- contribution,
- trust formation,
- credibility formation,
- credit formation,
- temporal coordination,
- coordination boundary,
- coexistent systems, and
- continuation,

can be implemented in one concrete institutional setting.

#### Mapping of Trust Framework layers into SIM F (informal)

| Trust layer             | SIM F illustration (marine market)                            |
|-------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|
| Contribution            | Premium − loss delivered per period (per agent, per voyage)  |
| Trust formation         | Owner and market renewal decisions, ORR paths                |
| Credibility formation   | Stable line share and market allocation over time            |
| Credit formation        | Capital and RC committed to shared risks                     |
| Temporal coordination   | Multi‑turn evolution of capital, float, and renewal cycles   |
| Coordination boundary   | Line allocation rules, prudential and investor constraints   |
| Coexistent systems      | Three doctrines coexisting on the same voyages               |
| Continuation            | Solvent active vs runoff vs trust collapse vs insolvency     |

The Trust Framework itself does not depend on any specific simulation. SIM F is deliberately presented as a separate, optional case study. 

All definitions and results in Parts 1–3 remain valid whether or not a particular application like SIM F is used. 

The advantage of SIM F is that it allows the abstract statements about trust, credibility and continuation to be tested and illustrated in a controlled environment.

The same pattern can be replicated in other domains (bank funding markets, clearing houses, platforms) without depending on any marine‑specific assumptions.

Although this application uses a marine insurance market, the structure of SIM F is deliberately generic:


agents with doctrines and capital,


shared exposures,


bilateral trust and renewal decisions, and


multiple institutional failure nodes.


The same pattern can be translated into other institutional settings (for example, interbank funding networks or clearing membership), providing a reusable blueprint for capability‑lens applications of the Trust Framework.

